    { q: "What risks does a viability review mechanism pose to your organisation's development programme, and how do you mitigate them?", a: "Key risks include: (1) surplus capture reducing cross-subsidy available for pipeline schemes — mitigated by modelling worst-case VRM outcomes in the original appraisal and presenting these to the board; (2) timing uncertainty — a late-stage review can delay final unit sales and cashflow — mitigated by negotiating clear trigger definitions and maximum review periods (e.g., 10 weeks); (3) cost definition disputes — mitigated by precise S106 drafting on allowable costs; (4) reputational risk if LPA perceives RP as resisting legitimate clawback — mitigated by transparent engagement and using RICS-compliant independent reviewers. At Latimer, I ensure VRM exposure is flagged in every investment committee paper." },
    { q: "If a viability review triggers additional affordable housing, can you draw Homes England grant for those units?", a: "Not automatically. AHP grant is allocated against a defined programme. Additional units triggered by a VRM were not in the original Homes England bid, so they require either a contract variation or a new bid submission. Furthermore, the additionality principle means grant should not replace contributions the developer would have funded anyway — if the VRM surplus fully funds the additional units, layering grant risks breaching additionality. In practice, I would discuss with our Homes England relationship manager early to explore whether the additional units qualify for grant, and ensure our S106 drafting preserves flexibility for commuted sums as an alternative to on-site delivery where grant is not available." },
    { q: "How does the surplus-sharing ratio in a viability review differ between GLA policy and outer London/non-London boroughs, and how would you negotiate this?", a: "The GLA's standard position is 60% to affordable housing and 40% to the developer. However, individual London boroughs may adopt different ratios in their local plan policies or SPDs — some go to 50:50, others to 70:30 in the LPA's favour. Outside London, there is no standard — it is entirely a matter of negotiation and local plan policy. I would negotiate by reference to: (a) the need to maintain development incentive for the RP (our 40% share supports pipeline delivery), (b) comparables from recent consents in the borough, (c) the overall affordable housing quantum being delivered, and (d) the argument that for RP-led schemes the surplus retained by the developer is itself recycled into affordable housing — unlike a private housebuilder retaining profit for shareholders. This argument has been accepted by several LPAs as justification for a more favourable split." }
